1
00:00:02,171 --> 00:00:04,182
                              

2
00:00:31,741 --> 00:00:34,188
                              

3
00:00:57,423 --> 00:00:59,400
         (Joe coughing)         

4
00:01:00,977 --> 00:01:02,953
             Hey. You all right?

5
00:01:04,330 --> 00:01:05,669
Need something cold.            

6
00:01:05,704 --> 00:01:07,212
            Hey, how's that flu?

7
00:01:07,247 --> 00:01:09,324
 That cough doesn't sound good. 

8
00:01:09,359 --> 00:01:10,899
     I don't know why not.      

9
00:01:10,968 --> 00:01:13,615
    I've been practicing it     
        all night.              

10
00:01:13,684 --> 00:01:17,673

11
00:01:17,610 --> 00:01:21,580
 "You Give Me Fever"        

11
00:01:59,648 --> 00:02:00,988
                 No, no, no, no,
                I understand.   

12
00:02:01,022 --> 00:02:02,966
                 I don't live in
             your area, but I...

13
00:02:03,034 --> 00:02:05,312
     I've called all the clinics
        around us, and, well,   

14
00:02:05,347 --> 00:02:08,095
         they all seem to be out
             of the flu vaccine.

15
00:02:08,164 --> 00:02:09,638
             N-no, I understand.

16
00:02:09,673 --> 00:02:11,414
                  The very young
            and the very old.   

17
00:02:11,449 --> 00:02:12,856
                The thing is, my
                 husband's sick,

18
00:02:12,891 --> 00:02:14,633
                 and I'm worried
             that if I get sick,

19
00:02:14,668 --> 00:02:15,975
            there's not going   
                    to be anyone

20
00:02:16,009 --> 00:02:17,952
                 to take care of
                 our three kids.

21
00:02:21,105 --> 00:02:22,813
            You can?            
        (chuckles)              

22
00:02:22,849 --> 00:02:24,188
        You will?               

23
00:02:24,222 --> 00:02:25,529
              Oh.               

24
00:02:25,597 --> 00:02:27,541
             11:45.             

25
00:02:27,575 --> 00:02:31,866
    Um, is there any way you    
could do that any earlier?      

26
00:02:31,901 --> 00:02:34,883
    It's just that Chandler     
  is so far from where I work.  

27
00:02:35,924 --> 00:02:36,962
You know what, never mind.      

28
00:02:36,996 --> 00:02:38,001
          Never mind.           

29
00:02:38,036 --> 00:02:39,375
    11:45. I will be there.     

30
00:02:39,444 --> 00:02:41,120
Don't give anyone my shot.      

31
00:02:41,187 --> 00:02:43,198
            Thanks.             

32
00:02:43,299 --> 00:02:44,640
Boy, you sure seem happy        

33
00:02:44,707 --> 00:02:46,483
for someone that's going        
to get a shot.                  

34
00:02:46,518 --> 00:02:47,590
          Yeah, I am.           

35
00:02:47,658 --> 00:02:49,199
    You guys are lucky          
    you got yours at school,    

36
00:02:49,233 --> 00:02:51,244
but I missed mine at work,      
 and with Daddy sick and all... 

37
00:02:51,279 --> 00:02:53,223
      Mom, do you want me       
      to take that to Dad       

38
00:02:53,291 --> 00:02:55,669
            so that you can, uh,
            have some breakfast?

39
00:02:55,738 --> 00:02:56,775
        Would you?              

40
00:02:56,878 --> 00:02:57,950
                        Yeah.   

41
00:02:57,984 --> 00:02:59,056
            Thanks.             

42
00:02:59,124 --> 00:03:00,397
BRIDGETTE:                      
Hey, Mom?                       

43
00:03:00,431 --> 00:03:02,945
      How's that detective      
      you work with doing?      

44
00:03:02,980 --> 00:03:04,354
              Detective Scanlon?

45
00:03:04,421 --> 00:03:05,594
              He's good.        

46
00:03:05,628 --> 00:03:07,337
         He's got a beautiful   
          little baby girl.     

47
00:03:07,438 --> 00:03:08,377
                  Yeah.         

48
00:03:08,444 --> 00:03:09,348
          He's good. Definitely.

49
00:03:09,450 --> 00:03:10,623
             Why do you ask?    

50
00:03:10,657 --> 00:03:12,534
I just had this dream last night

51
00:03:12,568 --> 00:03:15,014
  that didn't make much sense.  

52
00:03:15,050 --> 00:03:17,362
             What kind of dream?

53
00:03:17,430 --> 00:03:18,534
     It was nothing really.     

54
00:03:18,569 --> 00:03:20,781
  I mean, he was just sitting   
        in a restaurant         

55
00:03:20,815 --> 00:03:24,234
 with this pretty blonde lady,  
     and he was really sad.     

56
00:03:24,269 --> 00:03:25,240
He had                          
this little box,                

57
00:03:25,274 --> 00:03:27,018
and I think there               
was a ring in it.               

58
00:03:27,052 --> 00:03:30,136
     But the big thing is,      
    he was just really sad.     

59
00:03:30,170 --> 00:03:32,816
But, uh, that doesn't           
make sense, right?              

60
00:03:32,852 --> 00:03:34,762
     I mean, if he already      
          has a baby,           

61
00:03:34,796 --> 00:03:37,007
     then why was he giving     
    this lady a ring?           

62
00:03:37,043 --> 00:03:39,824
 And what would have to happen  
      to make him so sad?       

63
00:03:39,858 --> 00:03:41,501
      I don't know, honey.      

64
00:03:41,535 --> 00:03:43,445
         Those are all          
     really good questions.     

65
00:03:43,480 --> 00:03:46,764
  Hmm. So, you don't think it   
 makes much sense, either, huh? 

66
00:03:48,241 --> 00:03:50,016
             Cool.              

67
00:03:51,258 --> 00:03:52,799
     (elevator bell dings)      

68
00:03:55,951 --> 00:03:57,560
        (coughing)              

69
00:04:02,456 --> 00:04:05,170
     (sniffing)                 

70
00:04:05,205 --> 00:04:07,115
         (man coughing)         

71
00:04:18,113 --> 00:04:20,928
SCANLON:                        
So, what do you think?          

72
00:04:20,962 --> 00:04:23,040
Good ring, nice ring?           

73
00:04:23,107 --> 00:04:24,717
             It's very good.    

74
00:04:24,751 --> 00:04:27,096
              It's very nice.   

75
00:04:27,131 --> 00:04:28,538
You think Lynn will like it?    

76
00:04:29,579 --> 00:04:31,321
Well, of course, she'll like it.

77
00:04:31,390 --> 00:04:32,662
         Who wouldn't?          

78
00:04:32,730 --> 00:04:33,735
        (chuckles)              

79
00:04:33,770 --> 00:04:35,009
 I was thinking maybe tonight.  

80
00:04:35,043 --> 00:04:36,283
    Figure it's time.           

81
00:04:36,351 --> 00:04:37,590
I wait much longer,             
little Leigh                    

82
00:04:37,626 --> 00:04:39,870
will be old enough              
to be the maid of honor.        
                (chuckles)      

83
00:04:41,313 --> 00:04:43,424
        Boy, there's a lot of   
    strangers around here today.

84
00:04:43,459 --> 00:04:45,402
                What's going on?

85
00:04:45,437 --> 00:04:47,716
            SCANLON:            
 It's a big hush-hush briefing  
    with some guy from FEMA.    

86
00:04:47,784 --> 00:04:49,761
    You're not going?           
                      Not going.

87
00:04:49,863 --> 00:04:51,605
         Wasn't asked.          
    Damn glad about it, too.    

88
00:04:51,639 --> 00:04:53,952
I have somewhere to be at 11:45.

89
00:05:00,792 --> 00:05:03,172
              MAN:              
This picture was taken in 1996. 

90
00:05:03,206 --> 00:05:05,249
    The subject lived           
    in a small village          

91
00:05:05,285 --> 00:05:08,234
in the Democratic Republic      
         of the Congo.          

92
00:05:08,268 --> 00:05:11,990
He succumbed to a disease       
called viral hemorrhagic fever. 

93
00:05:12,057 --> 00:05:14,402
        It's very rare.         

94
00:05:14,437 --> 00:05:18,292
The strain responsible for this 
  man's death is called FV-39.  

95
00:05:18,326 --> 00:05:20,036
     Ladies and gentlemen,      

96
00:05:20,070 --> 00:05:23,087
          FV-39 is of           
    particular concern to us    

97
00:05:23,121 --> 00:05:27,077
because the virus holds up well 
in transport and weaponization. 

98
00:05:27,144 --> 00:05:29,054
 In fact, there are a few of us 

99
00:05:29,089 --> 00:05:31,938
      who believe that it       
    would be an ideal agent     

100
00:05:31,972 --> 00:05:34,452
for a bioterrorist attack       
against the United States.      

101
00:05:34,486 --> 00:05:36,129
          (man coughs)          

102
00:05:36,163 --> 00:05:38,174
      FEMA has been trying      
    to create an antiserum,     

103
00:05:38,208 --> 00:05:39,950
  a cure that can be deployed   

104
00:05:39,985 --> 00:05:42,967
in the event of just such       
     a bioterrorist attack.     

105
00:05:43,036 --> 00:05:44,643
  In fact, we've been working   
          very closely          

106
00:05:44,679 --> 00:05:46,287
with a company right here       
        in Phoenix              

107
00:05:46,321 --> 00:05:48,936
    that is at the forefront    
        of that effort.         

108
00:05:48,970 --> 00:05:51,550
Dr. Erik Westphal heads up      

109
00:05:51,585 --> 00:05:54,836
the bio-pathology division      
of United Southfield.           

110
00:05:54,904 --> 00:05:56,545
I'll let him take it            
from here.                      

111
00:05:56,580 --> 00:05:57,954
    Doctor.                     

112
00:05:57,989 --> 00:05:59,630
     Um... (clears throat)      

113
00:05:59,664 --> 00:06:03,050
     Our lab is a biosafety     
        level four lab.         

114
00:06:03,084 --> 00:06:04,525
 That means we're handling some 

115
00:06:04,559 --> 00:06:06,738
of the deadliest microbes       
         on the planet.         

116
00:06:06,772 --> 00:06:09,755
Uh, naturally, both our company 
and the federal government      

117
00:06:09,789 --> 00:06:12,806
  spend extraordinary amounts   
    of time and money           

118
00:06:12,841 --> 00:06:15,153
monitoring our inventory.       

119
00:06:16,629 --> 00:06:19,914
 When the government inspectors 
      gathered their data       

120
00:06:19,948 --> 00:06:21,456
and filed their latest reports, 

121
00:06:21,558 --> 00:06:23,300
         there appeared         
      to be trace amounts       

122
00:06:23,335 --> 00:06:26,519
of FV-39 cultures missing       
from some of our samples.       

123
00:06:26,553 --> 00:06:27,591
          (murmuring)           

124
00:06:27,660 --> 00:06:29,134
This isn't                      
the kind of thing               

125
00:06:29,169 --> 00:06:31,448
     that you would notice      
     on a day-to-day basis,     

126
00:06:31,515 --> 00:06:34,096
        but over time...        

127
00:06:34,131 --> 00:06:37,281
  There is a measurable amount  
          of this bug           

128
00:06:37,316 --> 00:06:39,694
         that we simply         
    can't account for.          

129
00:06:39,762 --> 00:06:41,069
          (murmuring)           

130
00:06:41,104 --> 00:06:43,383
MAN:                            
Worst case scenario,            
ladies and gentlemen,           

131
00:06:43,417 --> 00:06:45,930
  is that someone either sold   
     or gave these cultures     

132
00:06:45,965 --> 00:06:47,808
        to someone              
    who intends to use them     

133
00:06:47,842 --> 00:06:49,887
          as a weapon           
      of mass destruction.      

134
00:06:49,954 --> 00:06:52,099
        We at FEMA              
      need to move forward      

135
00:06:52,133 --> 00:06:53,742
 as though that were the case.  

136
00:06:53,776 --> 00:06:55,184
DINOVI:                         
So, what does this mean?        

137
00:06:55,219 --> 00:06:57,263
            Is Homeland Security
     issuing some kind of alert?

138
00:06:57,297 --> 00:06:58,804
              MAN:              
      Quite the contrary.       

139
00:06:58,839 --> 00:07:00,783
    There will be no alert.     

140
00:07:00,817 --> 00:07:02,761
 There will be no notification. 

141
00:07:02,795 --> 00:07:04,672
        There will be no        
      public announcement       

142
00:07:04,741 --> 00:07:05,979
of any kind.                    

143
00:07:06,047 --> 00:07:07,421
As a matter of fact,            

144
00:07:07,456 --> 00:07:09,533
        the only people         
  who know anything about this  

145
00:07:09,568 --> 00:07:11,411
          are sitting           
    in this room right now,     

146
00:07:11,479 --> 00:07:14,730
      and that is the way       
    it's got to stay.           

147
00:07:14,764 --> 00:07:18,586
  Dr. Westphal doesn't happen   
  to agree with that decision,  

148
00:07:18,620 --> 00:07:20,999
but the fact is, at this moment,
     ladies and gentlemen,      

149
00:07:21,067 --> 00:07:23,380
         we do not have         
     an effective antiserum     

150
00:07:23,415 --> 00:07:25,626
    in sufficient quantities    
    to deal with this.          

151
00:07:25,660 --> 00:07:27,806
          As a result,          
    the preventive measures     

152
00:07:27,840 --> 00:07:29,850
 that we can take are limited.  

153
00:07:29,886 --> 00:07:32,700
Dr. Westphal,                   
if this virus--                 

154
00:07:32,735 --> 00:07:35,617
this FV-39--                    
is out there,                   

155
00:07:35,652 --> 00:07:37,260
how bad could it get?           

156
00:07:37,328 --> 00:07:39,137
How many people                 
would be affected?              

157
00:07:40,143 --> 00:07:41,249
            It's hard to say.   

158
00:07:41,284 --> 00:07:42,893
                     It's not an
                 airborne virus.

159
00:07:42,927 --> 00:07:45,105
                 It is spread by
              people, to people,

160
00:07:45,172 --> 00:07:48,692
      and it carries a mortality
              rate of about 85%,

161
00:07:48,727 --> 00:07:50,906
which is what makes it          
such an effective threat.       

162
00:07:50,973 --> 00:07:53,655
Again, depending                
on how long it was out there    

163
00:07:53,689 --> 00:07:57,678
and how soon we were able       
        to contain it...        

164
00:07:57,712 --> 00:07:59,756
    hundreds of dead?           

165
00:07:59,824 --> 00:08:02,572
    Thousands, maybe.           

166
00:08:02,608 --> 00:08:05,858
    It's just too hard          
        to say for sure.        

167
00:08:07,000 --> 00:08:08,573
              JOE:              
    You did the right thing.    

168
00:08:08,642 --> 00:08:09,949
        (coughing)              

169
00:08:10,017 --> 00:08:11,591
  There's nothing to be gained  

170
00:08:11,626 --> 00:08:14,273
        by telling a man        
 who's contemplating proposing  

171
00:08:14,307 --> 00:08:17,760
      that it might not--       
 and I underline "might not"--  

172
00:08:17,795 --> 00:08:20,074
  go exactly the way he hopes.  

173
00:08:20,141 --> 00:08:21,213
         Yeah, I know.          

174
00:08:21,248 --> 00:08:22,654
         But you should         
      have seen his face.       

175
00:08:22,724 --> 00:08:23,829
    He looked so vulnerable.    

176
00:08:23,863 --> 00:08:25,773
I just... I hate the idea       

177
00:08:25,807 --> 00:08:27,650
         of him getting         
    his feelings hurt.          

178
00:08:27,684 --> 00:08:29,393
  Well, if Bridgette's right,   

179
00:08:29,428 --> 00:08:31,405
    he's going to get           
    his feelings hurt           

180
00:08:31,439 --> 00:08:32,881
    no matter what you do--     

181
00:08:32,915 --> 00:08:36,065
    um, either by you or...     
     or at dinner tonight.      

182
00:08:36,168 --> 00:08:37,473
              Huh.              

183
00:08:37,541 --> 00:08:38,714
         Well, thanks.          

184
00:08:38,748 --> 00:08:40,658
  That... that... that helps.   

185
00:08:40,693 --> 00:08:42,100
That feels better. Thanks.      

186
00:08:42,203 --> 00:08:43,207
         Anything else?         

187
00:08:43,242 --> 00:08:45,687
         Oh, uh, honey,         
     can you do me a favor?     

188
00:08:45,722 --> 00:08:47,833
        I'm running late        
        for my flu shot,        

189
00:08:47,869 --> 00:08:49,509
     and I left the number      
         of the clinic          

190
00:08:49,544 --> 00:08:50,784
 in the kitchen on the counter. 

191
00:08:50,818 --> 00:08:52,192
    Can you go read it to me    

192
00:08:52,226 --> 00:08:54,304
     so I can let them know     
     that I'm still coming?     

193
00:08:54,338 --> 00:08:56,517
    You want me to go           
all the way back to the kitchen?

194
00:08:56,551 --> 00:08:58,059
         Honey, please.         
    (tires screeching)          

195
00:08:58,093 --> 00:09:00,674
    I don't want them           
to give away my flu shot.       

196
00:09:11,136 --> 00:09:12,575
        You still there?        

197
00:09:12,611 --> 00:09:14,185
     I think there's going      
    to be an accident.          

198
00:09:14,253 --> 00:09:15,291
             What?              

199
00:09:15,327 --> 00:09:16,331
Honey, hang up the phone.       

200
00:09:16,366 --> 00:09:17,471
        Call 911.               

201
00:09:17,506 --> 00:09:18,879
 Tell them to send an ambulance 

202
00:09:18,914 --> 00:09:21,125
to North Beeline Highway,       
 just south of Shea Boulevard.  

203
00:09:21,160 --> 00:09:22,600
Tell them to send a fire truck. 

204
00:09:22,634 --> 00:09:24,076
         There's a man          
     who's about to crash,      

205
00:09:24,111 --> 00:09:26,355
    and he's got a backseat     
    full of gasoline.           

206
00:09:43,857 --> 00:09:44,929
          Sir!                  

207
00:09:44,997 --> 00:09:46,773
                Sir! Wake up!   

208
00:09:46,808 --> 00:09:48,450
            (coughs)            

209
00:09:48,484 --> 00:09:50,159
          Sir, sir, wake up!    

210
00:09:50,194 --> 00:09:51,668
What are you doing?             

211
00:09:51,703 --> 00:09:53,512
         Get out of the car now.

212
00:09:55,926 --> 00:09:57,737
      Your car's on fire.       
    You have to get out now.    

213
00:09:57,771 --> 00:09:59,211
     No. Get away!              

214
00:09:59,246 --> 00:10:00,720
    Get away from me!           

215
00:10:00,755 --> 00:10:01,960
         Open the door!         

216
00:10:01,995 --> 00:10:04,006
    Go away! Get away!          

217
00:10:04,073 --> 00:10:05,548
    You have to get out now.    

218
00:10:05,617 --> 00:10:07,090
  Your car's going to explode.  

219
00:10:07,192 --> 00:10:08,332
        Get away!               
                             No.

220
00:10:08,366 --> 00:10:10,409
I want to die, damn it!         

221
00:10:10,445 --> 00:10:11,415
        Go!                     

222
00:10:11,484 --> 00:10:12,455
                      It's going
                     to explode!

223
00:10:12,522 --> 00:10:15,405
Go! Go!                         

224
00:10:21,441 --> 00:10:25,529
          (explosion)           

225
00:10:25,563 --> 00:10:26,635
            I just don't get it.

226
00:10:26,669 --> 00:10:27,976
                    I mean, what
                    is the point

227
00:10:28,045 --> 00:10:29,552
            of dreaming about   
    something like this if...   

228
00:10:29,586 --> 00:10:31,161
            if you can't stop   
              it from happening?

229
00:10:31,196 --> 00:10:33,274
Well, I wish I had              
an answer for you.              

230
00:10:33,308 --> 00:10:35,352
I'm just glad he                
didn't take you with him.       

231
00:10:35,387 --> 00:10:37,330
Did, uh... did he               
say anything to you             

232
00:10:37,398 --> 00:10:38,872
before the car                  
blew up?                        

233
00:10:38,906 --> 00:10:40,381
         No, he just kept saying

234
00:10:40,416 --> 00:10:43,063
          that he wasn't getting
                 out of the car.

235
00:10:43,098 --> 00:10:46,683
        He kept telling me to   
          go away over and over.

236
00:10:47,724 --> 00:10:50,607
Look, uh, the driver            
was determined to do            

237
00:10:50,641 --> 00:10:52,619
what he was determined to do.   

238
00:10:52,653 --> 00:10:54,998
He turned his car into a bomb.  

239
00:10:55,033 --> 00:10:57,781
Even if you had managed         
to get him out of it,           

240
00:10:57,849 --> 00:10:59,659
don't you think that ultimately 
he would have found             

241
00:10:59,694 --> 00:11:01,235
some other way                  
to get the job done?            

242
00:11:01,269 --> 00:11:03,950
            (sighs)             

243
00:11:03,984 --> 00:11:06,565
            Oh, God.            

244
00:11:11,997 --> 00:11:15,114
            (sighs)             

