00:22:02,916 --> 00:22:04,859
    don't have an antivirus,    
          by the way.           

489
00:22:04,928 --> 00:22:06,201
  It's just that we don't have  
         enough funding         

490
00:22:06,235 --> 00:22:08,716
  to produce it in meaningful   
          quantities.           

491
00:22:08,750 --> 00:22:11,733
 It's about two cents a person, 
        actually.               

492
00:22:11,767 --> 00:22:15,454
 I mean, if every U.S. citizen  
        paid two cents,         

493
00:22:15,488 --> 00:22:18,437
 we'd have enough to inoculate  
  the entire city of Phoenix.   

494
00:22:18,505 --> 00:22:20,282
        Or Philadelphia.        

495
00:22:20,316 --> 00:22:23,400
        Or San Antonio.         

496
00:22:23,434 --> 00:22:25,444
    Just astounding, right?     

497
00:22:30,005 --> 00:22:31,983
          NEWSCASTER:           
 ...with the new increase       

498
00:22:32,051 --> 00:22:35,335
     and the mystery virus,     
nobody knows very much about it.

499
00:22:35,370 --> 00:22:37,146
        A short time ago        
it was completely unknown.      

500
00:22:37,214 --> 00:22:38,855
            How are you feeling?

501
00:22:38,891 --> 00:22:40,867
              Hey.              

502
00:22:40,902 --> 00:22:42,879
Pretty amazing, actually.       

503
00:22:42,914 --> 00:22:45,896
    They hydrated me,           
 they gave me some antibiotics. 

504
00:22:45,931 --> 00:22:47,908
Hell of a house call.           

505
00:22:47,943 --> 00:22:49,718
How about you?                  

506
00:22:49,786 --> 00:22:51,562
        I'm fine.               

507
00:22:51,596 --> 00:22:52,836
    It-it's all gone.           

508
00:22:52,871 --> 00:22:54,680
  The achiness. The dizziness.  

509
00:22:54,748 --> 00:22:56,155
 He said it was all in my head. 

510
00:22:56,223 --> 00:22:59,039
     I guess he was right.      

511
00:22:59,073 --> 00:23:02,358
Did anyone explain this to you, 
what they were doing here?      

512
00:23:02,393 --> 00:23:03,597
No one had to.                  

513
00:23:03,633 --> 00:23:05,710
It's all over the TV.           

514
00:23:05,745 --> 00:23:08,727
Representatives from FEMA       
and a Phoenix biotech firm      

515
00:23:08,762 --> 00:23:10,236
        began showing up        
        on the doorsteps        

516
00:23:10,271 --> 00:23:12,750
  of police and rescue workers  
before dawn this morning,       

517
00:23:12,818 --> 00:23:15,701
  concerned that they may have  
contracted a deadly virus.      

518
00:23:15,735 --> 00:23:18,684
So far none of the city workers 
      have tested positive      

519
00:23:18,753 --> 00:23:20,127
      and officials remain      
          tight-lipped          

520
00:23:20,195 --> 00:23:22,139
 about whether or not the virus 
        remains a threat        

521
00:23:22,173 --> 00:23:23,413
    to the general populace.    

522
00:23:23,447 --> 00:23:26,396
So much for secrets.            

523
00:23:26,431 --> 00:23:28,408
     (elevator bell dings)      

524
00:23:37,963 --> 00:23:39,974
     (elevator bell dings)      

525
00:23:42,289 --> 00:23:44,300
        (phones ringing)        

526
00:23:53,989 --> 00:23:55,799
                        DEVALOS:
        You feeling left out?   

527
00:23:55,834 --> 00:23:56,972
                You want one?   

528
00:23:57,040 --> 00:23:58,549
        A mask, I mean.         

529
00:23:58,583 --> 00:24:00,225
 I know a guy who knows a guy.  

530
00:24:00,260 --> 00:24:01,599
        Oh, no, no, no.         
        I'm holding out         

531
00:24:01,634 --> 00:24:03,779
for one of those full body suits

532
00:24:03,813 --> 00:24:06,696
    that those guys who came    
 to my house this morning had.  

533
00:24:06,730 --> 00:24:09,176
          Lot of fear.          

534
00:24:09,211 --> 00:24:12,194
      About 20% of the staff are
          taking a personal day.

535
00:24:12,228 --> 00:24:14,406
About to have a little briefing 
    in the conference room.     

536
00:24:14,508 --> 00:24:15,613
    You want to come along?     

537
00:24:15,681 --> 00:24:17,659
             Yeah.              

538
00:24:19,101 --> 00:24:20,676
     As soon as we realized     

539
00:24:20,710 --> 00:24:23,694
that this Lomis fellow had been 
infected with the missing virus 

540
00:24:23,728 --> 00:24:26,375
  and the fact that he worked   
     for United Southfield,     

541
00:24:26,411 --> 00:24:28,320
    we began investigating.     

542
00:24:28,354 --> 00:24:31,874
  Dr. Westphal gave us access   
    to his office computers,    

543
00:24:31,909 --> 00:24:34,723
and we obtained a warrant       
    for his laptop as well.     

544
00:24:35,764 --> 00:24:37,674
  We discovered that Mr. Lomis  

545
00:24:37,708 --> 00:24:39,082
    had been using an alias     

546
00:24:39,116 --> 00:24:42,200
      to log onto several       
    anti-American Web sites,    

547
00:24:42,234 --> 00:24:46,055
and that he had indeed contacted
a potential buyer for the virus.

548
00:24:46,089 --> 00:24:48,067
     Now the good news is,      

549
00:24:48,101 --> 00:24:51,520
the e-mails indicate that       
 the sale was never completed.  

550
00:24:51,556 --> 00:24:55,578
Our best guess is that Mr. Lomis
 inadvertently infected himself 

551
00:24:55,612 --> 00:24:57,924
      as he was attempting      
    to dispose of the virus     

552
00:24:57,959 --> 00:25:01,444
  as soon he realized that the  
 sale was not going to happen.  

553
00:25:01,479 --> 00:25:04,260
         We now believe         

554
00:25:04,328 --> 00:25:08,150
  that everything that he had   
        was in that car.        

555
00:25:08,184 --> 00:25:12,005
We believe that everything      
that he had burned up with him. 

556
00:25:13,347 --> 00:25:15,324
    And so I'm pleased          
to inform you this morning      

557
00:25:15,358 --> 00:25:17,169
that even as we're sitting here,

558
00:25:17,203 --> 00:25:19,683
the mayor's office is announcing
     to the general public      

559
00:25:19,718 --> 00:25:23,204
    that there is no longer     
any threat from the FV-39 virus.

560
00:25:29,105 --> 00:25:31,450
    And just when you think     

561
00:25:31,485 --> 00:25:33,428
that there is nothing good      

562
00:25:33,463 --> 00:25:36,312
  that can come from something  
  potentially so frightening,   

563
00:25:36,346 --> 00:25:39,162
the folks on Capitol Hill       
      woke up this morning      

564
00:25:39,197 --> 00:25:42,179
and heard about the panic       
that was slowly spreading       

565
00:25:42,214 --> 00:25:44,191
throughout the Southwest,       

566
00:25:44,226 --> 00:25:47,208
and I've been told that an      
 appropriation is in the works  

567
00:25:47,243 --> 00:25:49,756
    to allocate $60 million     

568
00:25:49,790 --> 00:25:52,807
    for the production          
      of FV-39 antiserum.       

569
00:25:59,045 --> 00:26:01,021
Looks like we're all            
going to live.                  

570
00:26:01,056 --> 00:26:03,871
Which means I'll get            
another shot at this.           

571
00:26:03,905 --> 00:26:06,888
        Oh, I'm sorry last night
            didn't go the way   
                 that you hoped.

572
00:26:06,922 --> 00:26:08,229
Eh, it's okay.                  

573
00:26:08,264 --> 00:26:09,939
If it was meant to be,          
it would've been.               

574
00:26:09,974 --> 00:26:11,214
     You know, it's funny.      

575
00:26:11,248 --> 00:26:13,057
  One of my daughters told me   
    yesterday morning           

576
00:26:13,092 --> 00:26:14,934
      that she had a dream      
      about you proposing.      

577
00:26:14,969 --> 00:26:17,081
So I kinda knew it wasn't going 
     to happen last night.      

578
00:26:17,115 --> 00:26:18,287
              Why?              

579
00:26:18,322 --> 00:26:21,002
When did she have me proposing? 

580
00:26:21,037 --> 00:26:22,210
              No.               

581
00:26:22,312 --> 00:26:25,261
     It wasn't about when.      

582
00:26:25,296 --> 00:26:27,306
You know what? Never mind.      
  Forget that I said anything.  

583
00:26:27,374 --> 00:26:28,915
 I promised myself I wouldn't.  

584
00:26:28,949 --> 00:26:30,826
Well, wait a minute. Don't      
 let me make a fool of myself.  

585
00:26:30,860 --> 00:26:32,235
      If there's something      
        I should know...        

586
00:26:32,302 --> 00:26:34,313
      No. There's nothing       
        you should know.        

587
00:26:37,231 --> 00:26:38,873
            (sighs):            
        I mean...               

588
00:26:38,907 --> 00:26:40,616
you were sad last night, right? 

589
00:26:40,651 --> 00:26:42,962
    We both were. We thought    
  the world was going to end.   

590
00:26:42,997 --> 00:26:44,471
    Okay, well, that was it.    

591
00:26:44,506 --> 00:26:45,779
      That was her dream.       

592
00:26:45,880 --> 00:26:48,494
    That she saw you getting    
        ready to propose        

593
00:26:48,530 --> 00:26:50,440
but instead you were sad.       

594
00:26:50,474 --> 00:26:52,485
    So, it already happened.    
You have nothing to worry about.

595
00:26:52,519 --> 00:26:54,731
            DINOVI:             
 How you doing out there?       

596
00:26:54,765 --> 00:26:57,245
Just getting locked and loaded. 

597
00:26:58,955 --> 00:27:00,397
                 I hate to leave
                    you guys,   

598
00:27:00,465 --> 00:27:01,705
            but I've had this   
             dinner on the books

599
00:27:01,773 --> 00:27:02,911
            with the head of the
                 Teacher's Union

600
00:27:02,979 --> 00:27:04,151
        for weeks.              

601
00:27:04,186 --> 00:27:05,359
          Are you sure          
    you're going to be okay?    

602
00:27:05,393 --> 00:27:07,035
Mm-hmm. Better than okay.       

603
00:27:07,069 --> 00:27:08,912
        Hi, cutes.              

604
00:27:09,013 --> 00:27:10,958
     Hi.                        
            So this woman I'm   
                meeting with?   

605
00:27:11,025 --> 00:27:12,935
        She has a reputation for
      being kind of long-winded.

606
00:27:13,037 --> 00:27:14,209
      I wouldn't wait up.       

607
00:27:14,244 --> 00:27:15,718
Hey, as soon                    
as she hits the hay,            

608
00:27:15,754 --> 00:27:17,730
I'm hitting the hay.            
    Uh, what else, what else?   

609
00:27:17,765 --> 00:27:19,373
        Uh, I've got my cell,   

610
00:27:19,441 --> 00:27:21,250
            the phone number for
                the restaurant's
                  on the fridge,

611
00:27:21,285 --> 00:27:22,458
                and, uh...      
You know what, Lynn?            

612
00:27:22,492 --> 00:27:24,134
          We're good.           

613
00:27:24,168 --> 00:27:25,508
         You just go do         
    what you gotta do.          

614
00:27:25,610 --> 00:27:27,151
          Okay, okay.           

615
00:27:27,185 --> 00:27:28,325
        I'm going.              

616
00:27:28,392 --> 00:27:29,531
              Mmm.              

617
00:27:29,633 --> 00:27:31,543
                  Okay.         
Oh, Mama.                       

618
00:27:31,644 --> 00:27:33,018
Oh, Mama.                       
                    Bye.        

619
00:27:33,086 --> 00:27:35,398
(laughs)                        
            Bye, honey. Bye.    

620
00:27:35,467 --> 00:27:37,477
          (whispers):           
              Bye.              

621
00:27:47,804 --> 00:27:51,256
       I've been working       
      on the baby bottle       

622
00:27:51,324 --> 00:27:54,273
 All the live long day        

623
00:27:54,342 --> 00:27:57,459
       I've been working       
      on the baby bottle       

624
00:27:57,527 --> 00:27:59,840
  Just to pass the time away  

625
00:27:59,874 --> 00:28:01,651
         (phone rings)          

626
00:28:01,718 --> 00:28:04,701
         Can't you hear        
    the phone a-ringing...     

627
00:28:04,735 --> 00:28:06,377
What do you think, little Leigh?

628
00:28:06,411 --> 00:28:08,892
  Should we let the answering   
    machine grab that?          

629
00:28:08,926 --> 00:28:10,904
    (machine clicks, beeps)     
         I'm with you.          

630
00:28:10,938 --> 00:28:12,244
     Hi, Lynn. It's Jenny.      

631
00:28:12,312 --> 00:28:13,921
    I just left this message    
          on your cell          

632
00:28:13,955 --> 00:28:16,401
and I called your apartment and 
 then I found this number, too, 

633
00:28:16,436 --> 00:28:18,916
and thought maybe I'd catch you 
     here, but I guess not.     

634
00:28:18,951 --> 00:28:20,928
          Anyway, uh,           
     Larry Birkbaum called.     

635
00:28:20,963 --> 00:28:22,939
He wanted to let you know       
 he's running a half hour late  

636
00:28:22,974 --> 00:28:24,784
      for dinner tonight.       
          Oh, and, uh,          

637
00:28:24,818 --> 00:28:26,627
he can't wait to see you.       

638
00:28:26,662 --> 00:28:27,834
         Okay. Thanks.          

639
00:28:27,903 --> 00:28:29,074
          That's all.           

640
00:28:33,769 --> 00:28:35,779
        (kissing)               

641
00:28:39,402 --> 00:28:40,877
    What was that for?          

642
00:28:40,911 --> 00:28:42,485
That was for                    
"I'm feeling better."           

643
00:28:42,520 --> 00:28:45,302
  That was for "I haven't been  
able to kiss you in days."      

644
00:28:45,403 --> 00:28:47,179
                    (giggles)   

645
00:28:47,214 --> 00:28:48,520
That was for...                 

646
00:28:48,554 --> 00:28:51,035
"nobody's going to get          
a deadly virus                  

647
00:28:51,069 --> 00:28:53,214
        "and bleed from their   
                  eyes and nose,

648
00:28:53,282 --> 00:28:56,265
             get things all over
            their face and die."

649
00:28:56,299 --> 00:28:59,283
            Not tonight, anyway.

650
00:28:59,317 --> 00:29:02,266
That's a good answer.           

651
00:29:02,301 --> 00:29:03,640
                     What a day.

652
00:29:03,709 --> 00:29:05,082
    Ugh.                        

653
00:29:06,189 --> 00:29:08,938
            How many            
almost disasters are there      

654
00:29:08,972 --> 00:29:10,916
that we never hear about?       

655
00:29:10,983 --> 00:29:13,933
Government or big business      
         don't tell us          

656
00:29:14,069 --> 00:29:15,375
  because they don't have to.   

657
00:29:15,409 --> 00:29:17,387
  Makes you grateful there are  
    people like that doctor     

658
00:29:17,421 --> 00:29:18,594
who was here this morning.      

659
00:29:18,628 --> 00:29:20,203
            Mm-hmm.             

660
00:29:24,261 --> 00:29:26,238
          Mmm.                  

661
00:29:26,272 --> 00:29:27,646
What was that one for?          

662
00:29:27,680 --> 00:29:29,289
                That was to hold
                me till morning.

663
00:29:29,323 --> 00:29:32,339
      Another good answer.      

664
00:29:34,687 --> 00:29:36,665
    (knocking on door)          
        WESTPHAL:               
           Come on in.          

665
00:29:37,672 --> 00:29:40,185
Okay, Erik, I'm here.           

666
00:29:40,220 --> 00:29:42,297
What's so important you needed  
to get me out of bed            

667
00:29:42,398 --> 00:29:43,839
at 11:30 and rush over?         

668
00:29:43,873 --> 00:29:47,694
     Don't get mad at me...     

669
00:29:47,730 --> 00:29:49,874
but I hacked into your computer.

670
00:29:49,908 --> 00:29:52,958
      I read your e-mail.       

671
00:29:55,038 --> 00:29:58,021
It's not happening, is it?      

672
00:29:58,055 --> 00:30:00,066
I'm sorry.                      

673
00:30:03,017 --> 00:30:06,000
    They don't buy it.          

674
00:30:06,034 --> 00:30:07,845
  They all think it's a setup.  

675
00:30:07,879 --> 00:30:10,493
     That maybe I'm working     
      with the government.      

676
00:30:12,506 --> 00:30:14,751
     So it's not happening.     

677
00:30:14,786 --> 00:30:17,768
Maybe you picked the wrong guy. 

678
00:30:19,546 --> 00:30:22,328
    I think deep down,          

679
00:30:22,395 --> 00:30:26,216
 I don't want to be the one who 
 sells this virus to some nuts. 

680
00:30:26,250 --> 00:30:29,267
     Gets a lot of innocent     
          people hurt.          

681
00:30:30,945 --> 00:30:33,928
        I mean...               

682
00:30:33,962 --> 00:30:35,973
     I'd do it if I had to.     

683
00:30:36,008 --> 00:30:38,990
  You think you don't have to?  

684
00:30:39,025 --> 00:30:42,008
You see Congress approving      
  production of our antiserum?  

685
00:30:42,076 --> 00:30:44,019
  Neither do I. You know why?   

686
00:30:44,088 --> 00:30:47,037
Because they can't see microbes.

687
00:30:47,072 --> 00:30:49,216
They can see planes flying      
        into buildings.         

688
00:30:49,250 --> 00:30:52,233
 They can see suicide bombers.  

689
00:30:52,301 --> 00:30:54,211
  But they can't see microbes.  

690
00:30:54,279 --> 00:30:57,262
(sniffling)                     

691
00:30:57,330 --> 00:30:59,878
                 Are you crying?

692
00:30:59,945 --> 00:31:02,962
    Oh, God, don't... don't cry.

693
00:31:02,997 --> 00:31:06,013
        I'm sorry.              

694
00:31:06,047 --> 00:31:08,830
          (sniffling)           

695
00:31:08,897 --> 00:31:10,874
 Are we going to be all right?  

696
00:31:10,909 --> 00:31:13,690
Are you asking me if there'll be
 money to pay for your alimony? 

697
00:31:13,725 --> 00:31:15,333
No.                             

698
00:31:15,434 --> 00:31:18,888
I'm asking you if we're         
going to be all right.          

699
00:31:23,347 --> 00:31:25,324
                 Come here.     

700
00:31:46,480 --> 00:31:49,095
  We're going to be just fine.  

701
00:31:51,107 --> 00:31:53,118
             Good.              

702
00:31:55,733 --> 00:31:56,906
             Wait, don't go yet.

703
00:31:56,940 --> 00:31:58,649
                  No, I want you
                    to see this.

704
00:31:58,683 --> 00:31:59,655
        See what?               

705
00:32:01,735 --> 00:32:03,143
              Me.               

706
00:32:03,177 --> 00:32:05,188
    Drinking the last           
    of the antiserum.           

707
00:32:05,256 --> 00:32:07,065
      I don't understand.       

708
00:32:07,133 --> 00:32:08,305
    Why are you doing that?     

709
00:32:08,340 --> 00:32:11,356
    Well, it's the only way     
         I can survive.         

710
00:32:13,838 --> 00:32:16,686
 I had to expose myself to the  
 virus in order to infect you.  

711
00:32:16,722 --> 00:32:18,732
     And now that I'm sure      
         you have it...         

712
00:32:18,766 --> 00:32:20,911
        Are you serious?        

713
00:32:20,946 --> 00:32:22,922
 You got about 12 hours, Mitch. 

714
00:32:22,990 --> 00:32:24,599
         Be a good guy.         

715
00:32:24,667 --> 00:32:26,611
    Go out and infect           
        lots of people.         

716
00:32:26,646 --> 00:32:28,455
        Or don't.               

717
00:32:28,523 --> 00:32:31,003
    As long as they find your   
      body covered with lesions,

718
00:32:31,071 --> 00:32:34,624
    blood running from your eyes
    and nose, what do I care?   

719
00:32:34,692 --> 00:32:36,032
          Do me favor.          

720
00:32:36,100 --> 00:32:38,009
Close the door on your way out. 

721
00:32:43,039 --> 00:32:45,016
          Mrs. Dubois.          

722
00:32:45,084 --> 00:32:46,793
          Come on in.           

723
00:32:47,867 --> 00:32:49,810
Oh, uh,                         
we better not.                  

724
00:32:49,879 --> 00:32:51,722
  Little bit of a cold.         

725
00:32:51,757 --> 00:32:53,499
It's good to see you again.     

726
00:32:53,566 --> 00:32:54,706
(clears throat)                 

727
00:32:54,740 --> 00:32:56,416
Hope you're feeling better.     

728
00:32:56,450 --> 00:32:58,428
                 Oh, physically,
                    much better.

729
00:33:00,003 --> 00:33:01,545
      Certainly busy here.      

730
00:33:01,613 --> 00:33:04,462
Oh, we have antiserum           
to manufacture.                 

731
00:33:04,496 --> 00:33:06,574
We're finally getting           
to do the work                  

732
00:33:06,642 --> 00:33:08,720
that we were meant to do.       

733
00:33:08,754 --> 00:33:11,670
      Feels good.               

734
00:33:11,738 --> 00:33:14,520
So, um, what can I do for you?  

735
00:33:14,554 --> 00:33:16,733
      Well, you can admit       

736
00:33:16,767 --> 00:33:19,415
    that you murdered           
    your friend, Dr. Lomis,     

737
00:33:19,449 --> 00:33:25,013
and that this entire panic      
about FV-39 virus is contrived. 

738
00:33:26,322 --> 00:33:28,500
 Why would you say that?        

739
00:33:30,715 --> 00:33:33,228
Why would you even think that?  

740
00:33:34,905 --> 00:33:36,849
 None of that is true.          

741
00:33:36,883 --> 00:33:38,022
     None of it.                

742
00:33:38,057 --> 00:33:39,866
      (coughing)                

743
00:33:43,856 --> 00:33:45,197
     Please, Dr. Westphal.      

744
00:33:45,231 --> 00:33:47,543
  We both know that it's true.  

745
00:33:47,578 --> 00:33:49,991
    That you are a pompous,     
         self-consumed,         

746
00:33:50,059 --> 00:33:52,471
      self-aggrandized man      
    who thinks he's smarter     

747
00:33:52,506 --> 00:33:54,618
        and knows better        
      than everybody else.      

748
00:33:54,652 --> 00:33:57,133
     You infected Dr. Lomis     
        with that virus,        

749
00:33:57,167 --> 00:34:00,049
    and you didn't even care    
     who else he infected.      

750
00:34:00,084 --> 00:34:01,658
    In fact, it was only due    

751
00:34:01,726 --> 00:34:04,173
    to Dr. Lomis's own sense    
        of decency              

752
00:34:04,241 --> 00:34:06,922
    that other people           
    didn't get sick and die.    

753
00:34:06,956 --> 00:34:09,369
Where is this coming from?      

754
00:34:09,403 --> 00:34:11,514
         This... story?         

755
00:34:11,549 --> 00:34:13,392
    It's not a story.           

756
00:34:13,426 --> 00:34:15,874
You know it's not a story.      

757
00:34:15,908 --> 00:34:18,388
 Well, can you prove any of it? 

758
00:34:22,646 --> 00:34:25,361
    You can't prove it          
     because it's not true.     

759
00:34:25,396 --> 00:34:28,211
  Just 'cause I can't prove it  
doesn't mean it's not so.       

760
00:34:28,246 --> 00:34:29,351
             Fine.              

761
00:34:29,386 --> 00:34:30,659
     Believe what you like.     

762
00:34:30,693 --> 00:34:32,201
    I have work to do.          

763
00:34:32,235 --> 00:34:33,609
    Lives to protect.           

764
00:34:34,683 --> 00:34:36,526
I'm going to go talk to my boss.

765
00:34:36,594 --> 00:34:39,141
Then I'm going to go talk       
     to that man from FEMA,     

766
00:34:39,175 --> 00:34:41,789
        and I'm going to tell   
            them what I know.   

767
00:34:41,857 --> 00:34:42,996
    And you're right.           

768
00:34:43,032 --> 00:34:44,773
I might not be able to prove it,

769
00:34:44,874 --> 00:34:47,925
but I might be able to get them 
     to take a second look      

770
00:34:47,992 --> 00:34:50,338
    at those appropriations     
      for your antiserum.       

771
00:34:50,374 --> 00:34:52,452
  I might be able to get them   

772
00:34:52,486 --> 00:34:55,937
    to put the brakes           
        on all of this.         

773
00:34:57,347 --> 00:34:59,358
     Why would you do that?     

774
00:35:01,403 --> 00:35:04,186
  Why would you deny hundreds   
     of thousands of people     

775
00:35:04,220 --> 00:35:06,934
 the chance to live in the face 
  of a potential catastrophe?   

776
00:35:06,969 --> 00:35:08,678
To prove what?                  

777
00:35:08,745 --> 00:35:11,494
To gain what?                   

778
00:35:12,669 --> 00:35:15,082
      Talk about pompous.       

779
00:35:15,116 --> 00:35:17,730
Self-aggrandized, self-consumed.

780
00:35:22,123 --> 00:35:24,100
(sighs)                         

781
00:35:32,349 --> 00:35:34,024
        (keys jangling)         

782
00:35:37,345 --> 00:35:39,187
                         DINOVI:
                    You're home.

783
00:35:39,255 --> 00:35:40,427
I wanted to surprise you.       

784
00:35:40,496 --> 00:35:41,501
    The baby's asleep.          

785
00:35:41,535 --> 00:35:42,842
     I was going to change.     

786
00:35:43,882 --> 00:35:45,893
    Something special?          

787
00:35:46,966 --> 00:35:49,379
    Uh, just things we need     
         to talk about.         

788
00:35:58,701 --> 00:36:00,241
     (sighs)                    

789
00:36:00,309 --> 00:36:01,985
      Talk.                     

790
00:36:03,897 --> 00:36:05,673
                I can't do it   
                      like this.

791
00:36:05,741 --> 00:36:07,215
                     Do you want
                      some wine?

792
00:36:07,249 --> 00:36:09,227
No. Let's just talk.            

793
00:36:09,261 --> 00:36:10,467
You got something on your mind. 

794
00:36:10,502 --> 00:36:11,708
I got something on my mind.     

795
00:36:11,743 --> 00:36:13,586
          I was asleep          
 when you got home last night.  

796
00:36:13,620 --> 00:36:15,463
        You were asleep         
  when I got up this morning.   

797
00:36:15,497 --> 00:36:17,139
 Let's just do it. Let's talk.  

798
00:36:19,689 --> 00:36:21,900
Okay, I'll start.               

799
00:36:22,940 --> 00:36:24,515
How is Larry Birkbaum?          

800
00:36:25,555 --> 00:36:27,130
              Wow.              

801
00:36:27,198 --> 00:36:29,109
        You know.               

802
00:36:30,182 --> 00:36:32,159
I'm a detective, Lynn.          

803
00:36:36,250 --> 00:36:37,758
Why is my...                    

804
00:36:39,737 --> 00:36:41,011
Why are you having dinner       

805
00:36:41,045 --> 00:36:42,922
         with a lawyer          
    who practices family law    

806
00:36:42,956 --> 00:36:44,765
      when you told me you      
         were working?          

807
00:36:44,800 --> 00:36:46,508
  I mean, this guy specializes  

808
00:36:46,543 --> 00:36:49,023
    in child support,           
        custody issues.         

809
00:36:49,058 --> 00:36:51,102
  Unless it's something else.   

810
00:36:51,170 --> 00:36:53,716
Maybe the two of you            
are friends.                    

811
00:36:53,751 --> 00:36:55,426
              No.               

812
00:37:01,898 --> 00:37:03,272
    What's this?                

813
00:37:03,307 --> 00:37:04,848
    That's my divorce.          

814
00:37:06,861 --> 00:37:08,871
             What?              

815
00:37:08,906 --> 00:37:10,145
        You're married?         

816
00:37:10,213 --> 00:37:11,552
                          I was.

817
00:37:11,587 --> 00:37:14,336
                For a minute,   
                      in my 20s.

818
00:37:14,437 --> 00:37:17,587
Oh, and now is probably as good 
  a time as any to tell you...  

819
00:37:17,622 --> 00:37:19,465
    I wasn't a virgin           
    when we first met.          

820
00:37:22,551 --> 00:37:24,025
                 I know I should
                    have just   

821
00:37:24,060 --> 00:37:25,266
    told you about it,          

822
00:37:25,334 --> 00:37:28,082
         but honestly,          
it meant so little to me.       

823
00:37:28,116 --> 00:37:29,993
     It lasted so briefly.      

824
00:37:30,027 --> 00:37:32,507
  And it happened so long ago.  

825
00:37:32,541 --> 00:37:34,720
    It was so inconsequential   
                to both of us   

826
00:37:34,787 --> 00:37:35,960
                  that we didn't
                     even bother

827
00:37:35,995 --> 00:37:38,073
            to get it taken care
                 of at the time.

828
00:37:38,107 --> 00:37:40,420
    And then, when you          
and I first got together,       

829
00:37:40,487 --> 00:37:42,397
    things were so on-again,    
        off-again.              

830
00:37:44,075 --> 00:37:46,353
                  But now, since
                we're on again--

831
00:37:46,388 --> 00:37:48,231
                     really on--

832
00:37:48,300 --> 00:37:50,176
                    I just...   

833
00:37:51,853 --> 00:37:54,199
        I hated...              

834
00:37:54,267 --> 00:37:56,579
I really hated keeping something
        from you.               

835
00:37:58,424 --> 00:38:00,871
            Also...             

836
00:38:24,943 --> 00:38:27,122
    It's never going to fit     
         on my finger.          

837
00:38:27,156 --> 00:38:29,167
        (chuckles)              
            Shut up.            

838
00:38:30,609 --> 00:38:31,950
        I want the knee.        

839
00:38:32,017 --> 00:38:33,425
    I want the whole thing.     

840
00:38:33,460 --> 00:38:35,236
             Okay.              

841
00:38:38,422 --> 00:38:40,935
But before that happens...      

842
00:38:43,048 --> 00:38:45,931
you're going to have to tell me 

843
00:38:45,965 --> 00:38:48,344
    what I'm supposed to do     
        with this.              

844
00:38:55,151 --> 00:38:57,128
         Okay, you win.         

845
00:38:58,873 --> 00:39:00,884
But I still want the knee.      

846
00:39:05,646 --> 00:39:07,253
         (sighs)                

847
00:39:20,430 --> 00:39:21,804
             Um...              

848
00:39:21,839 --> 00:39:26,833
unaccustomed to public speaking 
        as I am...              

849
00:39:26,868 --> 00:39:29,147
    God, this better get better.

850
00:39:29,214 --> 00:39:31,426
        (laughing)              

851
00:39:31,460 --> 00:39:33,337
(dog barking in distance)       

852
00:39:33,405 --> 00:39:35,617
                    Go to sleep.

853
00:39:35,651 --> 00:39:37,730
How do you know                 
I'm not sleeping?               

854
00:39:37,831 --> 00:39:39,774
    I'm just psychic.           

855
00:39:39,809 --> 00:39:42,356
Well, how am I                  
supposed to sleep               

856
00:39:42,390 --> 00:39:44,501
when I know...                  
I just...                       

857
00:39:44,535 --> 00:39:47,083
I know that                     
that evil bastard               

858
00:39:47,117 --> 00:39:49,362
is just sitting                 
in his house                    

859
00:39:49,397 --> 00:39:50,704
gloating to himself             

860
00:39:50,738 --> 00:39:52,480
about how he got away           
with everything.                

861
00:39:52,515 --> 00:39:54,325
I mean, he killed a man.        

862
00:39:54,359 --> 00:39:57,777
He marshaled the resources      
of an entire city--             

863
00:39:57,813 --> 00:40:00,997
the federal government, even--  
to get what he wanted.          

864
00:40:01,065 --> 00:40:03,277
            I don't know what to
              tell you, Allison.

865
00:40:03,311 --> 00:40:06,059
             Sometimes, you just
                have to give up.

866
00:40:06,094 --> 00:40:09,144
        Sometimes, you just have
        to surrender to the idea

867
00:40:09,178 --> 00:40:11,792
        that everything works   
                 out in the end.

868
00:40:13,135 --> 00:40:14,608
                That, one way   
                     or another,

869
00:40:14,643 --> 00:40:17,726
    life has a way of eventually
         evening everything out.

870
00:40:17,794 --> 00:40:20,275
              Even the gloating,
                evil bastards   

871
00:40:20,309 --> 00:40:22,789
                    are going to
                     get theirs.

872
00:40:22,823 --> 00:40:24,264
                      But it can
                     only happen

873
00:40:24,332 --> 00:40:26,242
                if we get a full
                  night's sleep.

874
00:40:26,276 --> 00:40:27,583
Are you mocking me?             

875
00:40:27,618 --> 00:40:30,132
            No, I'm begging you.

876
00:40:31,875 --> 00:40:34,155
            A grateful nation   
                    salutes you.

877
00:40:34,222 --> 00:40:35,563
Quiet.                          

878
00:40:35,597 --> 00:40:37,641
I'm trying to sleep.            

879
00:40:37,709 --> 00:40:39,652
 (monitor beeping rhythmically) 

880
00:40:39,687 --> 00:40:42,302
                            MAN:
        Good thing you called   
            911 when you did.   

881
00:40:42,336 --> 00:40:44,044
        (grunting)              

882
00:40:44,079 --> 00:40:45,888
      (labored breathing)       

883
00:40:45,956 --> 00:40:47,532
        (coughing)              
                            Shh.

884
00:40:47,600 --> 00:40:49,409
                     Just relax.

885
00:40:49,444 --> 00:40:51,990
                Dr. Westphal,   
            try not to speak.   

886
00:40:52,025 --> 00:40:54,940
     I know you're afraid,      
  but there's no reason to be.  

887
00:40:54,975 --> 00:40:58,596
  105 is a pretty good fever,   
      but we've seen more       

888
00:40:58,630 --> 00:41:00,472
    than a few patients come    
    through our doors           

889
00:41:00,575 --> 00:41:02,283
    with this very same flu     
        you have,               

890
00:41:02,351 --> 00:41:04,026
 and everyone's pulled through. 

891
00:41:04,095 --> 00:41:05,870
         We've just got         
     to keep you hydrated,      

892
00:41:05,939 --> 00:41:07,949
keep your electrolytes balanced,

893
00:41:07,983 --> 00:41:09,927
      and the medications       
      we're giving you...       

894
00:41:09,962 --> 00:41:12,978
    I'm betting we're looking   
              at 102 by morning.

895
00:41:20,858 --> 00:41:22,399
MAN:                            
Me?                             

896
00:41:22,467 --> 00:41:24,142
I'm betting 107.                

897
00:41:24,177 --> 00:41:26,456
But then your physician         
doesn't know you                

898
00:41:26,524 --> 00:41:28,031
as well as I do.                

899
00:41:28,099 --> 00:41:29,440
    He doesn't know you had     

900
00:41:29,475 --> 00:41:32,760
      an allergic reaction      
    to that antiserum.          

901
00:41:32,794 --> 00:41:35,777
  Sure, it cured the disease,   

902
00:41:35,811 --> 00:41:39,967
      kept you from dying       
  of viral hemorrhagic fever,   

903
00:41:40,001 --> 00:41:43,488
but we always knew              
a tiny part of the populace     

904
00:41:43,556 --> 00:41:45,633
would react badly               
to it.                          

905
00:41:45,668 --> 00:41:49,052
Which is why, when you          
felt that first itch            

906
00:41:49,087 --> 00:41:51,031
at the back                     
of your throat,                 

907
00:41:51,065 --> 00:41:53,110
must have been                  
a surprise, huh?                

908
00:41:53,177 --> 00:41:54,786
You didn't wait.                

909
00:41:54,821 --> 00:41:58,038
You gave yourself               
a massive dose of steroids      

910
00:41:58,072 --> 00:41:59,781
to halt the reaction.           

911
00:41:59,850 --> 00:42:03,268
Because you knew better.        

912
00:42:03,335 --> 00:42:07,594
    You were one step ahead,    
        as always.              

913
00:42:09,304 --> 00:42:13,863
     But you never counted      
          on the flu.           

914
00:42:13,897 --> 00:42:16,410
And now, with your immune system

915
00:42:16,478 --> 00:42:20,032
     completely compromised     
    by those steroids,          

916
00:42:20,066 --> 00:42:25,396
      your body has no way      
        to fight it off.        

917
00:42:25,430 --> 00:42:30,257
  You might as well have FV-39  
      or the black plague,      

918
00:42:30,291 --> 00:42:33,006
  for all the immune response   
        you can muster.         

919
00:42:35,320 --> 00:42:37,666
There you go.                   

920
00:42:37,735 --> 00:42:39,711
You go to sleep.                

921
00:42:39,780 --> 00:42:42,797
For the very last time.         

922
00:42:42,831 --> 00:42:45,143
That's right, Erik.             

923
00:42:45,178 --> 00:42:48,328
You are going to die.           

924
00:42:49,401 --> 00:42:51,479
        You know,               

925
00:42:51,547 --> 00:42:55,100
    I'd kiss you good night     
          if I could.           

926
00:42:55,169 --> 00:42:59,392
        But, hey,               
you can't have everything.      

927
00:42:59,459 --> 00:43:01,504
             Whoa.              

928
00:43:02,947 --> 00:43:04,119
    You okay?                   

929
00:43:04,154 --> 00:43:05,996
Everything all right?           

930
00:43:06,065 --> 00:43:08,209
                     It's better
                 than all right.

931
00:43:08,277 --> 00:43:09,953
             Everything's great.

932
00:43:16,022 --> 00:43:18,267
Don't worry about me.           

933
00:43:19,542 --> 00:43:21,553
I've totally surrendered.
